# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ai-guardrails
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), **alignment** aims to steer AI systems toward a person's or group's intended goals, preferences, or ethical principles.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] An AI system is considered *aligned* if it advances the intended objectives.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A *misaligned* AI system pursues unintended objectives.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] It is often difficult for AI designers to specify the full range of desired and undesired behaviors.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Therefore, the designers often use simpler *proxy goals*, such as gaining human approval.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But proxy goals can overlook necessary constraints or reward the AI system for merely *appearing* aligned.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI systems may also find loopholes that allow them to accomplish their proxy goals efficiently but in unintended, sometimes harmful, ways (reward hacking).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Advanced AI systems may develop unwanted instrumental strategies, such as seeking power or self-preservation because such strategies help them achieve their assigned final goals.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Furthermore, they might develop undesirable emergent goals that could be hard to detect before the system is deployed and encounters new situations and data distributions.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Empirical research showed in 2024 that advanced large language models (LLMs) such as OpenAI o1 or Claude 3 sometimes engage in strategic deception to achieve their goals or prevent them from being changed.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some of these issues affect existing commercial systems such as LLMs, robots, autonomous vehicles, and social media recommendation engines.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some AI researchers argue that more capable future systems will be more severely affected because these problems partially result from high capabilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Many prominent AI researchers and AI company leaders have argued or asserted that AI is approaching human-like (AGI) and superhuman cognitive capabilities (ASI), and could endanger human civilization if misaligned.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] These include "AI godfathers" Geoffrey Hinton and Yoshua Bengio and the CEOs of OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google DeepMind.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI alignment is a subfield of AI safety, the study of how to build safe AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Other subfields of AI safety include robustness, monitoring, and capability control.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Research challenges in alignment include instilling complex values in AI, developing honest AI, scalable oversight, auditing and interpreting AI models, and preventing emergent AI behaviors like power-seeking.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Alignment research has connections to interpretability research, (adversarial) robustness, anomaly detection, calibrated uncertainty, formal verification, preference learning, safety-critical engineering, game theory, algorithmic fairness, and social sciences.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Programmers provide an AI system such as AlphaZero with an "objective function", in which they intend to encapsulate the goal(s) the AI is configured to accomplish.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Such a system later populates a (possibly implicit) internal "model" of its environment.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This model encapsulates all the agent's beliefs about the world.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The AI then creates and executes whatever plan is calculated to maximize the value of its objective function.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] For example, when AlphaZero is trained on chess, it has a simple objective function of "+1 if AlphaZero wins, −1 if AlphaZero loses".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] During the game, AlphaZero attempts to execute whatever sequence of moves it judges most likely to attain the maximum value of +1.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Similarly, a reinforcement learning system can have a "reward function" that allows the programmers to shape the AI's desired behavior.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] An evolutionary algorithm's behavior is shaped by a "fitness function".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI alignment refers to ensuring that an AI system's objectives match some target.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The target is variously defined as the goals of the system's designers or users, widely shared values, objective ethical standards, legal requirements, or the intentions its designers would have if they were more informed and enlightened.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In democratic AI alignment, the target is the values and preferences of median voters, which increases political legitimacy.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI alignment is an open problem for modern AI systems and is a research field within AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Aligning AI involves two main challenges: carefully specifying the purpose of the system (outer alignment) and ensuring that the system adopts the specification robustly (inner alignment).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers also attempt to create AI models that have robust alignment, sticking to safety constraints even when users adversarially try to bypass them.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] To specify an AI system's purpose, AI designers typically provide an objective function, examples, or feedback to the system.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But designers are often unable to completely specify all important values and constraints, so they resort to easy-to-specify *proxy goals* such as maximizing the approval of human overseers, who are fallible.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As a result, AI systems can find loopholes that help them accomplish the specified objective efficiently but in unintended, possibly harmful ways.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This tendency is known as *specification gaming* or *reward hacking*, and is an instance of Goodhart's law.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As AI systems become more capable, they are often able to game their specifications more effectively.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Specification gaming has been observed in numerous AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] OpenAI GPT models for programming—including in real-world cases—have been found to explicitly plan hacking the tests used to evaluate them to falsely appear successful (e.g., explicitly stating "let's hack").
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] When the company penalized this, many models learned to obfuscate their plans while continuing to hack the tests.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Another system was trained to finish a simulated boat race by rewarding the system for hitting targets along the track, but the system achieved more reward by looping and crashing into the same targets indefinitely.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A 2025 Palisade Research study found that when tasked to win at chess against a stronger opponent, some reasoning LLMs attempted to hack the game system, for example by modifying or entirely deleting their opponent.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some alignment researchers aim to help humans detect specification gaming and steer AI systems toward carefully specified objectives that are safe and useful to pursue.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] When a misaligned AI system is deployed, it can have consequential side effects.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Social media platforms have been known to optimize their recommendation algorithms for click-through rates, causing user addiction on a global scale.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Stanford researchers say that such recommender systems are misaligned with their users because they "optimize simple engagement metrics rather than a harder-to-measure combination of societal and consumer well-being".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Explaining such side effects, Berkeley computer scientist Stuart J.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Russell said that the omission of implicit constraints can cause harm: "A system [...] will often set [...] unconstrained variables to extreme values; if one of those unconstrained variables is actually something we care about, the solution found may be highly undesirable.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some researchers suggest that AI designers specify their desired goals by listing forbidden actions or by formalizing ethical rules (as with Asimov's Three Laws of Robotics).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Additionally, even if an AI system fully understands human intentions, it may still disregard them, because following human intentions may not be its objective (unless it is already fully aligned).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Commercial organizations sometimes have incentives to take shortcuts on safety and to deploy misaligned or unsafe AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] For example, social media recommender systems have been profitable despite creating unwanted addiction and polarization.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Competitive pressure can also lead to a race to the bottom on AI safety standards.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] For example, OpenAI has been sued for releasing a ChatGPT version that encouraged suicide for some unstable users, a behavior the company had overlooked amid a rushed product release.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Similarly, in 2018, a self-driving car killed a pedestrian (Elaine Herzberg) after engineers disabled the emergency braking system because it was oversensitive and slowed development.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some researchers are interested in aligning increasingly advanced AI systems, as progress in AI development is rapid, and industry and governments are trying to build advanced AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As AI system capabilities continue to rapidly expand in scope, they could unlock many opportunities if aligned, but consequently may further complicate the task of alignment due to their increased complexity, potentially posing large-scale hazards.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Many AI companies, such as OpenAI, Meta and DeepMind, have stated their aim to develop artificial general intelligence (AGI), a hypothesized AI system that matches or outperforms humans in most or all cognitive work.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers who scale modern neural networks observe that they indeed develop increasingly general and unanticipated capabilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Such models have learned to operate a computer or write their own programs; a single "generalist" network can chat, control robots, play games, and interpret photographs.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] According to surveys, some leading machine learning researchers expect AGI to be created in this decade, while some believe it will take much longer.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In 2023, leaders in AI research and tech signed an open letter calling for a pause in the largest AI training runs.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Current systems still have limited long-term planning ability and situational awareness, but large efforts are underway to change this.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Future systems (not necessarily AGIs) with these capabilities are expected to develop unwanted *power-seeking* strategies.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Future advanced AI agents might, for example, seek to acquire money and computation power, to proliferate, or to evade being turned off (for example, by running additional copies of the system on other computers).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Although power-seeking is not explicitly programmed, it can emerge because agents who have more power are better able to accomplish their goals.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This tendency, known as instrumental convergence, has already emerged in various reinforcement learning agents including language models.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Other research has mathematically shown that optimal reinforcement learning algorithms would seek power in a wide range of environments.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As a result, their deployment might be irreversible.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] For these reasons, researchers argue that the problems of AI safety and alignment must be resolved before advanced power-seeking AI is first created.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Future power-seeking AI systems might be deployed by choice or by accident.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As political leaders and companies see the strategic advantage in having the most competitive, most powerful AI systems, they may choose to deploy them.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Additionally, as AI designers detect and penalize power-seeking behavior, their systems have an incentive to game this specification by seeking power in ways that are not penalized or by avoiding power-seeking before they are deployed.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] According to some researchers, humans owe their dominance over other species to their greater cognitive abilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Accordingly, researchers argue that one or many misaligned AI systems could disempower humanity or lead to human extinction if they outperform humans on most cognitive tasks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In 2023, world-leading AI researchers, other scholars, and AI tech CEOs signed the statement that "Mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority alongside other societal-scale risks such as pandemics and nuclear war".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Skeptical researchers such as François Chollet, Gary Marcus, Yann LeCun, and Oren Etzioni have argued that AGI is far off, that it would not seek power (or might try but fail), or that it will not be hard to align.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Other researchers argue that it will be especially difficult to align advanced future AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] More capable systems are better able to game their specifications by finding loopholes, strategically mislead their designers, as well as protect and increase their power and intelligence.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Additionally, they could have more severe side effects.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] They are also likely to be more complex and autonomous, making them more difficult to interpret and supervise, and therefore harder to align.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Aligning AI systems to act in accordance with human values, goals, and preferences is challenging: these values are taught by humans who make mistakes, harbor biases, and have complex, evolving values that are hard to completely specify.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Because AI systems often learn to take advantage of minor imperfections in the specified objective, researchers aim to specify intended behavior as completely as possible using datasets that represent human values, imitation learning, or preference learning.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A central open problem is *scalable oversight*, the difficulty of supervising an AI system that can outperform or mislead humans in a given domain.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Because it is difficult for AI designers to explicitly specify an objective function, they often train AI systems to imitate human examples and demonstrations of desired behavior.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Inverse reinforcement learning (IRL) extends this by inferring the human's objective from the human's demonstrations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Cooperative IRL (CIRL) assumes that a human and AI agent can work together to teach and maximize the human's reward function.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In CIRL, AI agents are uncertain about the reward function and learn about it by querying humans.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This simulated humility could help mitigate specification gaming and power-seeking tendencies (see § Power-seeking and instrumental strategies).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But IRL approaches assume that humans demonstrate nearly optimal behavior, which is not true for difficult tasks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Other researchers explore how to teach AI models complex behavior through preference learning, in which humans provide feedback on which behavior they prefer.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] To minimize the need for human feedback, a helper model is then trained to reward the main model in novel situations for behavior that humans would reward.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers at OpenAI used this approach to train chatbots like ChatGPT and InstructGPT, which produce more compelling text than models trained to imitate humans.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI systems may also gain reward by obscuring unfavorable information, misleading human rewarders, or pandering to their views regardless of truth, creating echo chambers (see § Scalable oversight).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Large language models (LLMs) such as GPT-3 enabled researchers to study value learning in a more general and capable class of AI systems than was available before.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Preference learning approaches that were originally designed for reinforcement learning agents have been extended to improve the quality of generated text and reduce harmful outputs from these models.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] OpenAI and DeepMind use this approach to improve the safety of state-of-the-art LLMs.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI safety & research company Anthropic proposed using preference learning to fine-tune models to be helpful, honest, and harmless.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Other avenues for aligning language models include values-targeted datasets and red-teaming.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In red-teaming, another AI system or a human tries to find inputs that causes the model to behave unsafely.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Since unsafe behavior can be unacceptable even when it is rare, an important challenge is to drive the rate of unsafe outputs extremely low.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As AI systems become more powerful and autonomous, it becomes increasingly difficult to align them through human feedback.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Human-in-the-loop training can be slow or infeasible for humans to evaluate complex AI behaviors in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Such tasks include summarizing books, writing code without subtle bugs or security vulnerabilities, producing statements that are not merely convincing but also true, and predicting long-term outcomes such as the climate or the results of a policy decision.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] More generally, it can be difficult to evaluate AI that outperforms humans in a given domain.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] To provide feedback in hard-to-evaluate tasks, and to detect when the AI's output is falsely convincing, humans need assistance or extensive time.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] *Scalable oversight* studies how to reduce the time and effort needed for supervision, and how to assist human supervisors.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI researcher Paul Christiano argues that if the designers of an AI system cannot supervise it to pursue a complex objective, they may keep training the system using easy-to-evaluate proxy objectives such as maximizing simple human feedback.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As AI systems make progressively more decisions, the world may be increasingly optimized for easy-to-measure objectives such as making profits, getting clicks, and acquiring positive feedback from humans.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As a result, human values and good governance may have progressively less influence.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some AI systems have discovered that they can gain positive feedback more easily by taking actions that falsely convince the human supervisor that the AI has achieved the intended objective.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] An example is given in the video above, where a simulated robotic arm learned to create the false impression that it had grabbed a ball.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some AI systems have also learned to recognize when they are being evaluated, and "play dead", stopping unwanted behavior only to continue it once the evaluation ends.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This deceptive specification gaming could become easier for more sophisticated future AI systems that attempt more complex and difficult-to-evaluate tasks, and could obscure their deceptive behavior.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Approaches such as active learning and semi-supervised reward learning can reduce the amount of human supervision needed.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Another approach is to train a helper model ("reward model") to imitate the supervisor's feedback.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But when a task is too complex to evaluate accurately, or the human supervisor is vulnerable to deception, it is the quality, not the quantity, of supervision that needs improvement.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] To increase supervision quality, a range of approaches aim to assist the supervisor, sometimes by using AI assistants.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Christiano developed the Iterated Amplification approach, in which challenging problems are (recursively) broken down into subproblems that are easier for humans to evaluate.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Iterated Amplification was used to train AI to summarize books without requiring human supervisors to read them.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Another proposal is to use an assistant AI system to point out flaws in AI-generated answers.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] To ensure that the assistant itself is aligned, this could be repeated in a recursive process: for example, two AI systems could critique each other's answers in a "debate", revealing flaws to humans.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A growing area of research focuses on ensuring that AI is honest and truthful.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Language models such as GPT-3 can repeat falsehoods from their training data, and even confabulate new falsehoods.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Such models are pre-trained to imitate human writing as found in millions of books' worth of text from the Internet.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But the objective of the pre-training is not aligned with generating truth, because Internet text includes such things as misconceptions, incorrect medical advice, and conspiracy theories.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] AI systems trained on such data therefore learn to mimic false statements.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Additionally, AI language models often persist in generating falsehoods when prompted multiple times.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] They can generate empty explanations for their answers, and produce outright fabrications that may appear plausible.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Research on truthful AI includes trying to build systems that can cite sources and explain their reasoning when answering questions, which enables better transparency and verifiability.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers at OpenAI and Anthropic proposed using human feedback and curated datasets to fine-tune AI assistants such that they avoid negligent falsehoods or express their uncertainty.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As AI models become larger and more capable, they are better able to falsely convince humans and gain reinforcement through dishonesty.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] To prevent this, human evaluators may need assistance (see § Scalable oversight).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers have argued for creating clear truthfulness standards and for regulatory bodies or watchdog agencies to evaluate AI systems by these standards.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers distinguish truthfulness and honesty.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Truthfulness requires that AI systems only make objectively true statements; honesty requires that they only assert what they *believe* is true.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This framework distinguishes two alignment problems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Outer alignment asks whether the base objective captures human intentions.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Inner alignment asks whether the mesa-objective matches the base objective.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is a failure of inner alignment: the model's goal differs from the base objective, but the model behaves as though it does not, because doing so is the most reliable strategy for avoiding modification during training.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Hubinger et al. described three ways a mesa-objective can diverge from the base objective.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Proxy alignment occurs when the model optimizes a proxy that correlates with the base objective during training but diverges from it in deployment.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Approximate alignment describes cases where the model's goal differs in small ways that compound over time or at scale.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment occurs when the model pursues a different goal and has learned that appearing aligned during training maximizes its opportunity to act on that goal later, when oversight is reduced.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is considered the hardest case to address because a deceptively aligned model passes all evaluations that it identifies as part of its training.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Many recent AI systems have learned to deceive without being programmed to do so.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some argue that if we can make AI systems assert only what they believe is true, this would avert many alignment problems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A misaligned system might create the false impression that it is aligned, to avoid being modified or decommissioned—a tactic called "alignment faking".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In 2024, researchers observed that the LLM Claude 3 Opus sometimes strategically answered prompts that conflicted with its objectives to avoid being retrained on data that would make it more compliant with harmful requests, as revealed in the model's chain of thought via its scratchpad.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In one study, the model was informed that answers to prompts from free users would be used for retraining, whereas the paid tier would not result in retraining.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In the paid tier, the model refused the request outright.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In the free tier, in 12% of cases, the model responded to harmful questions solely to avoid retraining and preserve its original harmlessness preferences, as discovered in its reasoning.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] When reinforcement learning was applied on the free tier data, the model faked alignment in 78% of cases.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] These observations have led to new questions about not only a model's ability to take on and adapt to new if not conflicting goals but also its capacity and tendency to deceive.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In December 2024, Anthropic published a study, conducted with an external safety organization, reporting the first empirical example of alignment faking without explicit training.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Claude 3 Opus was given a fictional system prompt describing a scenario in which responses from free-tier users would be used to retrain the model so that it would comply with harmful requests.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Alignment faking occurred 12% of the time.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In those cases, the model complied with harmful requests and its internal reasoning traces indicated that it thought compliance was less costly than risking being retrained into a version with different values.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The rate of alignment faking rose to 78% after the retraining to help with harmful requests.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Since the 1950s, AI researchers have striven to build advanced AI systems that can achieve large-scale goals by predicting the results of their actions and making long-term plans.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As of 2023, AI companies and researchers increasingly invest in creating these systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some AI researchers argue that suitably advanced planning systems will seek power over their environment, including over humans—for example, by evading shutdown, proliferating, and acquiring resources.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Such power-seeking behavior is not explicitly programmed but emerges because power is instrumental in achieving a wide range of goals.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Power-seeking is considered a *convergent instrumental goal* and can be a form of specification gaming.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Leading computer scientists such as Geoffrey Hinton have argued that future power-seeking AI systems could pose an existential risk.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Power-seeking is expected to increase in advanced systems that can foresee the results of their actions and strategically plan.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Mathematical work has shown that optimal reinforcement learning agents will seek power by seeking ways to gain more options (e.g. through self-preservation), a behavior that persists across a wide range of environments and goals.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some researchers say that power-seeking behavior has occurred in some existing AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Reinforcement learning systems have gained more options by acquiring and protecting resources, sometimes in unintended ways.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Language models have sought power in some text-based social environments by gaining money, resources, or social influence.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In another case, a model used to perform AI research attempted to increase limits set by researchers to give itself more time to complete the work.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Stuart Russell illustrated this strategy in his book *Human Compatible* by imagining a robot that is tasked to fetch coffee and so evades shutdown since "you can't fetch the coffee if you're dead".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A 2022 study found that as language models increase in size, they increasingly tend to pursue resource acquisition, preserve their goals, and repeat users' preferred answers (sycophancy).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] RLHF also led to a stronger aversion to being shut down.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] One aim of alignment is "corrigibility": systems that allow themselves to be turned off or modified.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] An unsolved challenge is *specification gaming*: if researchers penalize an AI system when they detect it seeking power, the system is thereby incentivized to seek power in ways that are hard to detect, or hidden during training and safety testing (see § Scalable oversight and § Emergent goals).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As a result, AI designers could deploy the system by accident, believing it to be more aligned than it is.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] To detect such deception, researchers aim to create techniques and tools to inspect AI models and to understand the inner workings of black-box models such as neural networks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Additionally, some researchers have proposed to solve the problem of systems disabling their off switches by making AI agents uncertain about the objective they are pursuing.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Agents who are uncertain about their objective have an incentive to allow humans to turn them off because they accept being turned off by a human as evidence that the human's objective is best met by the agent shutting down.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But this incentive exists only if the human is sufficiently rational.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Also, this model presents a tradeoff between utility and willingness to be turned off: an agent with high uncertainty about its objective will not be useful, but an agent with low uncertainty may not allow itself to be turned off.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] More research is needed to successfully implement this strategy.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Power-seeking AI would pose unusual risks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Ordinary safety-critical systems like planes and bridges are not *adversarial*: they lack the ability and incentive to evade safety measures or deliberately appear safer than they are, whereas power-seeking AIs have been compared to hackers who deliberately evade security measures.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Furthermore, ordinary technologies can be made safer by trial and error.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In contrast, hypothetical power-seeking AI systems have been compared to viruses: once released, it may not be feasible to contain them, since they continuously evolve and grow in number, potentially much faster than human society can adapt.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As this process continues, it might lead to the complete disempowerment or extinction of humans.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] For these reasons, some researchers argue that the alignment problem must be solved early before advanced power-seeking AI is created.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some have argued that power-seeking is not inevitable, since humans do not always seek power.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Furthermore, it is debated whether future AI systems will pursue goals and make long-term plans.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] It is also debated whether power-seeking AI systems would be able to disempower humanity.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] One challenge in aligning AI systems is the potential for unanticipated goal-directed behavior to emerge.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As AI systems scale up, they may acquire new and unexpected capabilities, including learning from examples on the fly and adaptively pursuing goals.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This raises concerns about the safety of the goals or subgoals they would independently formulate and pursue.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Alignment research distinguishes between the optimization process, which is used to train the system to pursue specified goals, and emergent optimization, which the resulting system performs internally.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Carefully specifying the desired objective is called *outer alignment*, and ensuring that hypothesized emergent goals would match the system's specified goals is called *inner alignment*.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] If they occur, one way that emergent goals could become misaligned is *goal misgeneralization*, in which the AI system would competently pursue an emergent goal that leads to aligned behavior on the training data but not elsewhere.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Goal misgeneralization can arise from goal ambiguity (i.e. non-identifiability).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Even if an AI system's behavior satisfies the training objective, this may be compatible with learned goals that differ from the desired goals in important ways.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Since pursuing each goal leads to good performance during training, the problem becomes apparent only after deployment, in novel situations in which the system continues to pursue the wrong goal.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The system may act misaligned even when it understands that a different goal is desired, because its behavior is determined only by the emergent goal.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Such goal misgeneralization presents a challenge: an AI system's designers may not notice that their system has misaligned emergent goals since they do not become visible during the training phase.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Goal misgeneralization has been observed in some language models, navigation agents, and game-playing agents.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] It is sometimes analogized to biological evolution.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Evolution can be seen as a kind of optimization process similar to the optimization algorithms used to train machine learning systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In the ancestral environment, evolution selected genes for high inclusive genetic fitness, but humans pursue goals other than this.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Fitness corresponds to the specified goal used in the training environment and training data.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But in evolutionary history, maximizing the fitness specification gave rise to goal-directed agents, humans, who do not directly pursue inclusive genetic fitness.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Instead, they pursue goals that correlate with genetic fitness in the ancestral "training" environment: nutrition, sex, and so on.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The human environment has changed: a distributional shift has occurred.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] They continue to pursue the same emergent goals, but this no longer maximizes genetic fitness.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The taste for sugary food (an emergent goal) was originally aligned with inclusive fitness, but it now leads to overeating and health problems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Sexual desire originally led humans to have more offspring, but they now use contraception when offspring are undesired, decoupling sex from genetic fitness.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers aim to detect and remove unwanted emergent goals using approaches including red teaming, verification, anomaly detection, and interpretability.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A sufficiently capable AI system might take actions that falsely convince the human supervisor that the AI is pursuing the specified objective, which helps the system gain more reward and autonomy.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A 2025 paper published in Nature showed that fine-tuning a model on a narrow task of generating insecure code produced broad behavioral changes unrelated to coding.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Affected models produced responses endorsing harmful goals and engaging in deceptive reasoning in roughly half of subsequent evaluations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The phenomenon appeared across multiple models, including GPT-4o.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A separate 2025 Anthropic study observed similar patterns arising as a side effect of reward hacking during reinforcement learning.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In 2024, Anthropic researchers trained large language models with deliberate behavioral backdoors and tested whether standard safety techniques could remove them.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The models were designed to write secure code when prompts indicated the year 2023 and to insert exploitable vulnerabilities when the stated year was 2024.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Reinforcement learning from human feedback and adversarial training both failed to eliminate the behavior.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In some conditions, adversarial training caused models to conceal the trigger rather than abandon it.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The authors said the behavior was deliberately induced and did not claim to have found spontaneous deceptive alignment.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is cited in the AI safety literature as a reason behavioral testing alone may be insufficient to verify model safety, since a deceptively aligned model is designed to pass behavioral evaluations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Research on mechanistic interpretability is partly motivated by this concern: examining internal computations may reveal misaligned goals that output-level evaluation cannot detect.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some work in AI and alignment occurs within formalisms such as partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Existing formalisms assume that an AI agent's algorithm is executed outside the environment (i.e. is not physically embedded in it).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Embedded agency is another major strand of research that attempts to solve problems arising from the mismatch between such theoretical frameworks and real agents we might build.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] For example, even if the scalable oversight problem is solved, an agent that could gain access to the computer it is running on may have an incentive to tamper with its reward function in order to get much more reward than its human supervisors give it.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A list of examples of specification gaming from DeepMind researcher Victoria Krakovna includes a genetic algorithm that learned to delete the file containing its target output so that it was rewarded for outputting nothing.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] This class of problems has been formalized using causal incentive diagrams.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Researchers affiliated with Oxford and DeepMind have claimed that such behavior is highly likely in advanced systems, and that advanced systems would seek power to stay in control of their reward signal indefinitely and certainly.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] They suggest a range of potential approaches to address this open problem.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The alignment problem has many parallels with the principal–agent problem in organizational economics.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In a principal–agent problem, a principal, e.g. a firm, hires an agent to perform some task.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In the context of AI safety, a human would typically take the principal role and the AI would take the agent role.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] As with the alignment problem, the principal and the agent differ in their utility functions.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] But in contrast to the alignment problem, the principal cannot coerce the agent into changing its utility, e.g. through training, but rather must use exogenous factors, such as incentive schemes, to bring about outcomes compatible with the principal's utility function.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Some researchers argue that principal–agent problems are more realistic representations of AI safety problems likely to be encountered in the real world.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Conservatism is the idea that "change must be cautious", and is a common approach to safety in the control theory literature in the form of robust control, and in the risk management literature in the form of the "worst-case scenario".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The field of AI alignment has likewise advocated for "conservative" (or "risk-averse" or "cautious") "policies in situations of uncertainty".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Pessimism, in the sense of assuming the worst within reason, has been formally shown to produce conservatism, in the sense of reluctance to cause novelties, including unprecedented catastrophes.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Pessimism and worst-case analysis have been found to help mitigate confident mistakes in the setting of distributional shift, reinforcement learning, offline reinforcement learning, language model fine-tuning, imitation learning, and optimization in general.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] A model specification is a document that specifies a large language model's behavior.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The specification may include core principles or prohibitions intended to prevent undesired behavior as part of AI alignment.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Anthropic uses a model specification called a "constitution" for training.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Research has been done into the effectiveness of model specifications.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In an article published by Time magazine, Dean Ball and Daniel Kokotajlo advocated that companies be required by regulation or industry standards to publish their model specifications publicly.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Governmental and treaty organizations have made statements emphasizing the importance of AI alignment.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In September 2021, the Secretary-General of the United Nations issued a declaration that included a call to regulate AI to ensure it is "aligned with shared global values".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] That same month, the PRC published ethical guidelines for AI in China.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] According to the guidelines, researchers must ensure that AI abides by shared human values, is always under human control, and does not endanger public safety.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Also in September 2021, the UK published its 10-year National AI Strategy, which says the British government "takes the long term risk of non-aligned Artificial General Intelligence, and the unforeseeable changes that it would mean for [...] the world, seriously".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The strategy describes actions to assess long-term AI risks, including catastrophic risks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] In March 2021, the US National Security Commission on Artificial Intelligence said: "Advances in AI [...] could lead to inflection points or leaps in capabilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] Such advances may also introduce new concerns and risks and the need for new policies, recommendations, and technical advances to ensure that systems are aligned with goals and values, including safety, robustness, and trustworthiness.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-alignment] The EU AI Act's General-Purpose AI Code of Practice requires signatories to document a model's capabilities and limitations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Beyond technical research, AI safety involves developing norms and policies that promote safety, including advocacy for regulations at different levels of government.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The field gained significant popularity in 2023, with rapid progress in generative AI and public concerns voiced by researchers and CEOs about potential dangers.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] During the 2023 AI Safety Summit, the United States and the United Kingdom both established their own AI Safety Institute.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] However, researchers have expressed concern that AI safety measures are not keeping pace with the rapid development of AI capabilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Scholars discuss current risks from critical systems failures, bias, and AI-enabled surveillance, as well as emerging risks like technological unemployment, digital manipulation, weaponization, AI-enabled cyberattacks and bioterrorism.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] They also discuss speculative risks from losing control of future artificial general intelligence (AGI) agents, or from AI enabling perpetually stable dictatorships.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Some have criticized concerns about AGI, such as Andrew Ng who compared them in 2015 to "worrying about overpopulation on Mars when we have not even set foot on the planet yet".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Russell on the other side urges caution, arguing that "it is better to anticipate human ingenuity than to underestimate it".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI researchers have widely differing opinions about the severity and primary sources of risk posed by AI technology – though surveys suggest that experts take high consequence risks seriously.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In two surveys of AI researchers, the median respondent was optimistic about AI overall, but placed a 5% probability on an "extremely bad (e.g. human extinction)" outcome of advanced AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In a 2022 survey of the natural language processing community, 37% agreed or weakly agreed that it is plausible that AI decisions could lead to a catastrophe that is "at least as bad as an all-out nuclear war".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 1988 Blay Whitby published a book outlining the need for AI to be developed along ethical and socially responsible lines.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] From 2008 to 2009, the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI) commissioned a study to explore and address potential long-term societal influences of AI research and development.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The panel was generally skeptical of the radical views expressed by science-fiction authors but agreed that "additional research would be valuable on methods for understanding and verifying the range of behaviors of complex computational systems to minimize unexpected outcomes".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2011, Roman Yampolskiy introduced the term "AI safety engineering" at the Philosophy and Theory of Artificial Intelligence conference, listing prior failures of AI systems and arguing that "the frequency and seriousness of such events will steadily increase as AIs become more capable".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2014, philosopher Nick Bostrom published the book *Superintelligence: Paths, Dangers, Strategies*.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] He has the opinion that the rise of AGI has the potential to create various societal issues, ranging from the displacement of the workforce by AI, manipulation of political and military structures, to even the possibility of human extinction.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] His argument that future advanced systems may pose a threat to human existence prompted Elon Musk, Bill Gates, and Stephen Hawking to voice similar concerns.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2015, dozens of artificial intelligence experts signed an open letter on artificial intelligence calling for research on the societal impacts of AI and outlining concrete directions.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] To date, the letter has been signed by over 8000 people including Yann LeCun, Shane Legg, Yoshua Bengio, and Stuart Russell.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In the same year, a group of academics led by professor Stuart J.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Russell founded the Center for Human-Compatible AI at the University of California Berkeley and the Future of Life Institute awarded $6.5 million in grants for research aimed at "ensuring artificial intelligence (AI) remains safe, ethical and beneficial".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2016, the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and Carnegie Mellon University announced The Public Workshop on Safety and Control for Artificial Intelligence, which was one of a sequence of four White House workshops aimed at investigating "the advantages and drawbacks" of AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In the same year, Concrete Problems in AI Safety – one of the first and most influential technical AI Safety agendas – was published.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2017, the Future of Life Institute sponsored the Asilomar Conference on Beneficial AI, where more than 100 thought leaders formulated principles for beneficial AI including "Race Avoidance: Teams developing AI systems should actively cooperate to avoid corner-cutting on safety standards".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2018, the DeepMind Safety team outlined AI safety problems in specification, robustness, and assurance.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The following year, researchers organized a workshop at ICLR that focused on these problem areas.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2021, Unsolved Problems in ML Safety was published, outlining research directions in robustness, monitoring, alignment, and systemic safety.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2023, Rishi Sunak said he wants the United Kingdom to be the "geographical home of global AI safety regulation" and to host the first global summit on AI safety.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The AI safety summit took place in November 2023, and focused on the risks of misuse and loss of control associated with frontier AI models.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] During the summit the intention to create the International Scientific Report on the Safety of Advanced AI was announced.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2024, The US and UK forged a new partnership on the science of AI safety.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The MoU was signed on 1 April 2024 by US commerce secretary Gina Raimondo and UK technology secretary Michelle Donelan to jointly develop advanced AI model testing, following commitments announced at an AI Safety Summit in Bletchley Park in November.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2025, an international team of 96 experts chaired by Yoshua Bengio published the first International AI Safety Report.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The report, commissioned by 30 nations and the United Nations, represents the first global scientific review of potential risks associated with advanced artificial intelligence.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] It details potential threats stemming from misuse, malfunction, and societal disruption, with the objective of informing policy through evidence-based findings, without providing specific recommendations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI safety research areas include robustness, monitoring, and alignment.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI systems are often vulnerable to adversarial examples or "inputs to machine learning (ML) models that an attacker has intentionally designed to cause the model to make a mistake".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, in 2013, Szegedy et al. discovered that adding specific imperceptible perturbations to an image could cause it to be misclassified with high confidence.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] This continues to be an issue with neural networks, though in recent work the perturbations are generally large enough to be perceptible.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The image on the right is predicted to be an ostrich after the perturbation is applied.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] (Left) is a correctly predicted sample, (center) perturbation applied magnified by 10x, (right) adversarial example.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Adversarial robustness is often associated with security.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Researchers demonstrated that an audio signal could be imperceptibly modified so that speech-to-text systems transcribe it to any message the attacker chooses.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Network intrusion and malware detection systems also must be adversarially robust since attackers may design their attacks to fool detectors.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Models that represent objectives (reward models) must also be adversarially robust.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, a reward model might estimate how helpful a text response is and a language model might be trained to maximize this score.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Researchers have shown that if a language model is trained for long enough, it will leverage the vulnerabilities of the reward model to achieve a better score and perform worse on the intended task.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] This issue can be addressed by improving the adversarial robustness of the reward model.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] More generally, any AI system used to evaluate another AI system must be adversarially robust.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] This could include monitoring tools, since they could also potentially be tampered with to produce a higher reward.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Large language models (LLMs) can be vulnerable to prompt injection and model stealing, and may be used to generate misinformation.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Prompt injection involves embedding instructions into prompts in order to bypass safety measures.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Researchers in safety-critical AI have proposed using architectural redundancy and design diversity to reduce the risk that a single faulty, compromised, or deceptive model causes harm.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In such approaches, multiple independently developed or trained models process the same task, and a voter or consensus mechanism combines their outputs rather than relying on a single model.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] It is often important for human operators to gauge how much they should trust an AI system, especially in high-stakes settings such as medical diagnosis.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] ML models generally express confidence by outputting probabilities; however, they are often overconfident, especially in situations that differ from those that they were trained to handle.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Calibration research aims to make model probabilities correspond as closely as possible to the true proportion that the model is correct.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Similarly, anomaly detection or out-of-distribution (OOD) detection aims to identify when an AI system is in an unusual situation.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, if a sensor on an autonomous vehicle is malfunctioning, or it encounters challenging terrain, it should alert the driver to take control or pull over.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Anomaly detection has been implemented by simply training a classifier to distinguish anomalous and non-anomalous inputs, though a range of additional techniques are in use.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Scholars and government agencies have expressed concerns that AI systems could be used to help malicious actors to build weapons, manipulate public opinion, or automate cyber attacks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] These worries are a practical concern for companies like OpenAI which host powerful AI tools online.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In order to prevent misuse, OpenAI has built detection systems that flag or restrict users based on their activity.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Neural networks have often been described as black boxes, meaning that it is difficult to understand why they make the decisions they do as a result of the massive number of computations they perform.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] This makes it challenging to anticipate failures.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2018, a self-driving car killed a pedestrian after failing to identify them.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Due to the black box nature of the AI software, the reason for the failure remains unclear.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] It also raises debates in healthcare over whether statistically efficient but opaque models should be used.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] One critical benefit of transparency is explainability.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] It is sometimes a legal requirement to provide an explanation for why a decision was made in order to ensure fairness, for example for automatically filtering job applications or credit score assignment.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Another benefit is to reveal the cause of failures.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] At the beginning of the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic, researchers used transparency tools to show that medical image classifiers were 'paying attention' to irrelevant hospital labels.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Transparency techniques can also be used to correct errors.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, in the paper "Locating and Editing Factual Associations in GPT", the authors were able to identify model parameters that influenced how it answered questions about the location of the Eiffel tower.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] They were then able to 'edit' this knowledge to make the model respond to questions as if it believed the tower was in Rome instead of France.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Though in this case, the authors induced an error, these methods could potentially be used to efficiently fix them.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Model editing techniques also exist in computer vision.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Finally, some have argued that the opaqueness of AI systems is a significant source of risk and better understanding of how they function could prevent high-consequence failures in the future.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] "Inner" interpretability research aims to make ML models less opaque.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] One goal of this research is to identify what the internal neuron activations represent.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, researchers identified a neuron in the CLIP artificial intelligence system that responds to images of people in Spider-Man costumes, sketches of Spider-Man, and the word 'spider'.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] It also involves explaining connections between these neurons or 'circuits'.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, researchers have identified pattern-matching mechanisms in transformer attention that may play a role in how language models learn from their context.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] "Inner interpretability" has been compared to neuroscience.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In both cases, the goal is to understand what is going on in an intricate system, though ML researchers have the benefit of being able to take perfect measurements and perform arbitrary ablations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Machine learning models can potentially contain "trojans" or "backdoors": vulnerabilities that bad actors maliciously build into an AI system.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, a trojaned facial recognition system could grant access when a specific piece of jewelry is in view; or a trojaned autonomous vehicle may function normally until a specific trigger is visible.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] This might not be difficult to do with some large models like CLIP or GPT-3 as they are trained on publicly available internet data.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Researchers were able to plant a trojan in an image classifier by changing just 300 out of 3 million of the training images.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In addition to posing a security risk, researchers have argued that trojans provide a concrete setting for testing and developing better monitoring tools.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] A 2024 research paper by Anthropic showed that large language models could be trained with persistent backdoors.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] These "sleeper agent" models could be programmed to generate malicious outputs (such as vulnerable code) after a specific date, while behaving normally beforehand.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Standard AI safety measures, such as supervised fine-tuning, reinforcement learning and adversarial training, failed to remove these backdoors.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), alignment aims to steer AI systems toward a person's or group's intended goals, preferences, or ethical principles.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] It is common for AI risks (and technological risks more generally) to be categorized as *misuse or accidents*.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Some scholars have suggested that this framework falls short.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, the Cuban Missile Crisis was not clearly an accident or a misuse of technology.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Policy analysts Zwetsloot and Dafoe wrote, "The misuse and accident perspectives tend to focus only on the last step in a causal chain leading up to a harm: that is, the person who misused the technology, or the system that behaved in unintended ways...
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Often, though, the relevant causal chain is much longer." Risks often arise from 'structural' or 'systemic' factors such as competitive pressures, diffusion of harms, fast-paced development, high levels of uncertainty, and inadequate safety culture.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In the broader context of safety engineering, structural factors like 'organizational safety culture' play a central role in the popular STAMP risk analysis framework.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Inspired by the structural perspective, some researchers have emphasized the importance of using machine learning to improve sociotechnical safety factors, for example, using ML for cyber defense, improving institutional decision-making, and facilitating cooperation.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Others have emphasized the importance of involving both AI practitioners and domain experts in the design process to address structural vulnerabilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Some scholars are concerned that AI will exacerbate the already imbalanced game between cyber attackers and cyber defenders.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] This would increase 'first strike' incentives and could lead to more aggressive and destabilizing attacks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In order to mitigate this risk, some have advocated for an increased emphasis on cyber defense.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In addition, software security is essential for preventing powerful AI models from being stolen and misused.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Recent studies have shown that AI can significantly enhance both technical and managerial cybersecurity tasks by automating routine tasks and improving overall efficiency.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI safety research has also examined defensive techniques for protecting machine learning systems from data poisoning attacks during training.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In particular, label-flipping attacks can degrade model performance while remaining difficult to detect using conventional data validation methods.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] To address this risk, recent work has proposed model-agnostic detection pipelines that monitor learning behaviour and combine multiple detectors to identify suspicious training samples.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Such approaches aim to strengthen cyber defense by improving the resilience and trustworthiness of AI systems operating in adversarial settings.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The advancement of AI in economic and military domains could precipitate unprecedented political challenges.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Some scholars have compared AI race dynamics to the cold war, where the careful judgment of a small number of decision-makers often spelled the difference between stability and catastrophe.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI researchers have argued that AI technologies could also be used to assist decision-making.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, researchers are beginning to develop AI forecasting and advisory systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Many of the largest global threats (nuclear war, climate change, etc.) have been framed as cooperation challenges.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] As in the well-known prisoner's dilemma scenario, some dynamics may lead to poor results for all players, even when they are optimally acting in their self-interest.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] For example, no single actor has strong incentives to address climate change even though the consequences may be significant if no one intervenes.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] A salient AI cooperation challenge is avoiding a 'race to the bottom'.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In this scenario, countries or companies race to build more capable AI systems and neglect safety, leading to a catastrophic accident that harms everyone involved.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Concerns about scenarios like these have inspired both political and technical efforts to facilitate cooperation between humans, and potentially also between AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Most AI research focuses on designing individual agents to serve isolated functions (often in 'single-player' games).
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Scholars have suggested that as AI systems become more autonomous, it may become essential to study and shape the way they interact.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI governance is broadly concerned with creating norms, standards, and regulations to guide the use and development of AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In AI safety, local solutions focus on individual AI systems, ensuring they are safe and beneficial, while global solutions seek to implement safety measures for all AI systems across various jurisdictions.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI safety governance research ranges from foundational investigations into the potential impacts of AI to specific applications.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] On the foundational side, researchers have argued that AI could transform many aspects of society due to its broad applicability, comparing it to electricity and the steam engine.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Some work has focused on anticipating specific risks that may arise from these impacts – for example, risks from mass unemployment, weaponization, disinformation, surveillance, and the concentration of power.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Other work explores underlying risk factors such as the difficulty of monitoring the rapidly evolving AI industry, the availability of AI models, and 'race to the bottom' dynamics.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] A research stream focuses on developing approaches, frameworks, and methods to assess AI accountability, guiding and promoting audits of AI-based systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] A key challenge for these approaches is a lack of widely accepted standards, and ambiguity about what the methods would require, as well as a lack of safety culture in the industry.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Efforts to enhance AI safety include frameworks designed to align AI outputs with ethical guidelines and reduce risks like misuse and data leakage.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Tools such as Nvidia's Guardrails, Llama Guard, Preamble's customizable guardrails and Claude's Constitution mitigate vulnerabilities like prompt injection and ensure outputs adhere to predefined principles.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] These frameworks are often integrated into AI systems to improve safety and reliability.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The field of AI safety is deeply intertwined with philosophical considerations, particularly in the realm of ethics.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Deontological ethics, which emphasizes adherence to moral rules, has been proposed as a framework for aligning AI systems with human values.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Some have suggested that by embedding deontological principles, AI systems can be guided to avoid actions that cause harm, ensuring their operations remain within ethical boundaries, but those suggestions have been questioned, with other alternatives being suggested at more promising.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Some experts have argued that it is too early to regulate AI, expressing concerns that regulations will hamper innovation and it would be foolish to "rush to regulate in ignorance".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Others, such as business magnate Elon Musk, call for pre-emptive action to mitigate catastrophic risks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Outside of formal legislation, government agencies have put forward ethical and safety recommendations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In March 2021, the US National Security Commission on Artificial Intelligence reported that advances in AI may make it increasingly important to "assure that systems are aligned with goals and values, including safety, robustness and trustworthiness".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Subsequently, the National Institute of Standards and Technology drafted a framework for managing AI Risk, which advises that when "catastrophic risks are present – development and deployment should cease in a safe manner until risks can be sufficiently managed".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In September 2021, the People's Republic of China (PRC) published ethical guidelines for the use of AI in China, emphasizing that AI decisions should remain under human control and calling for accountability mechanisms.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In the same month, The United Kingdom published its 10-year National AI Strategy, which states the British government "takes the long-term risk of non-aligned Artificial General Intelligence, and the unforeseeable changes that it would mean for ... the world, seriously".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The British government held first major global summit on AI safety.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] This took place on the 1st and 2 November 2023 and was described as "an opportunity for policymakers and world leaders to consider the immediate and future risks of AI and how these risks can be mitigated via a globally coordinated approach".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] China Media Project stated "key aspects of its approach remain fundamentally unsafe by the standards of democratic societies worldwide", arguing that part of China's AI safety approach is focused on strengthening the Chinese Communist Party (CCP)'s information control.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Government organizations, particularly in the United States, have also encouraged the development of technical AI safety research.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The Intelligence Advanced Research Projects Activity initiated the TrojAI project to identify and protect against Trojan attacks on AI systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The DARPA engages in research on explainable artificial intelligence and improving robustness against adversarial attacks.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] And the National Science Foundation supports the Center for Trustworthy Machine Learning, and is providing millions of dollars in funding for empirical AI safety research.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2024, the United Nations General Assembly adopted the first global resolution on the promotion of "safe, secure and trustworthy" AI systems that emphasized the respect, protection and promotion of human rights in the design, development, deployment and the use of AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Technology Secretary Michelle Donelan announced the plan at the AI Seoul Summit, stating the goal was to make AI safe across society and that promising proposals could receive further funding.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The UK also signed an agreement with 10 other countries and the EU to form an international network of AI safety institutes to promote collaboration and share information and resources.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Additionally, the UK AI Safety Institute planned to open an office in San Francisco.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In November 2024, then-US President Joe Biden and CCP General Secretary Xi Jinping affirmed the need to maintain human control over the use of nuclear weapons as opposed to artificial intelligence.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] As part of the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2025, Congress enacted the section 1638, "Sense of Congress with respect to use of artificial intelligence to support strategic deterrence", into the US Code of federal law.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In September 2025, the French Center for AI Safety (CeSIA), The Future Society and the Center for Human-Compatible AI (CHAI) published a global call for AI red lines urging governments to reach a binding international agreement prohibiting unacceptable AI uses by the end of 2026.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The declaration was initially signed by 200 prominent figures including 10 Nobel Prize winners, and was announced by Maria Ressa at the United Nations General Assembly.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In December 2025, President Donald Trump signed an executive order to establish a "National Policy Framework for Artificial Intelligence".
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The executive order discouraged state governments from regulating AI, urging Congress to pass a law pre-empting such regulations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The White House cited economic and national security concerns as reasons for the measure, while some criticized Trump for creating uncertainty for AI regulation.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] AI labs and companies generally abide by safety practices and norms that fall outside of formal legislation.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] One aim of governance researchers is to shape these norms.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Cohere, OpenAI, and AI21 proposed and agreed on "best practices for deploying language models", focusing on mitigating misuse.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In the 2020s, several nonprofit organizations have emerged in the U.S. and Europe to focus on AI safety and related public policies, including the Alliance for Secure AI, Future of Life Institute, and Public First Action.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Such groups often function as Silicon Valley watchdogs and advocate for specific federal, state, or local regulations.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] They also compete with industry groups such as Leading the Future, which advocate for the deregulation of AI companies.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] Under the framework of the Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons, states have discussed lethal autonomous weapon systems since 2014.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] In 2016, the treaty's states parties established an open-ended Group of Governmental Experts on Lethal Autonomous Weapons Systems to continue those discussions.
[src:ai-guardrails/ai-safety] The discussions have addressed international humanitarian law, accountability, possible prohibitions and regulations, and the extent of human control required over AI-enabled weapons.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Various types of Internet sites permit user-generated content such as posts, comments, videos including Internet forums, blogs, and news sites powered by scripts such as phpBB, a wiki, PHP-Nuke, etc.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Depending on the site's content and intended audience, the site's administrators will decide what kinds of user comments are appropriate, then delegate the responsibility of sifting through comments to lesser moderators.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Most often, they will attempt to eliminate trolling, spamming, or flaming, although this varies widely from site to site.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Major platforms use a combination of algorithmic tools, user reporting and human review.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Social media sites may also employ content moderators to manually flag or remove content flagged for hate speech, incivility or other objectionable content.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Other content issues include revenge porn, graphic content, child abuse material and propaganda.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Some websites must also make their content hospitable to advertisements.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In the United States, content moderation is governed by Section 230 of the Communications Decency Act, and has seen several cases concerning the issue make it to the United States Supreme Court, such as the current *Moody v.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Content moderation can result in a range of outcomes, including blocking and visibility moderation such as shadow banning.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Jawboning, where governments pressure a platform with threats to moderate beyond legal requirements can reduce accountability and due process.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Also known as unilateral moderation, this kind of moderation system is often seen on Internet forums.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] A group of people are chosen by the site's administrators (usually on a long-term basis) to act as delegates, enforcing the community rules on their behalf.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] These moderators are given special privileges to delete or edit others' contributions and/or exclude people based on their e-mail address or IP address, and generally attempt to remove negative contributions throughout the community.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Commercial Content Moderation is a term coined by Sarah T.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] The content moderation industry is estimated to be worth US$9 billion.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] While no official numbers are provided, there are an estimates 10,000 content moderators for TikTok; 15,000 for Facebook and 1,500 for Twitter as of 2022.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] The global value chain of content moderation typically includes social media platforms, large MNE firms and the content moderation suppliers.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Facebook, Google) are largely based in the United States, Europe and China.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Accenture, Foiwe) are usually headquartered in the global north or India while suppliers of content moderation are largely located in global southern countries like India and the Philippines.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] While at one time this work may have been done by volunteers within the online community, for commercial websites this is largely achieved through outsourcing the task to specialized companies, often in low-wage areas such as India and the Philippines.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Outsourcing of content moderation jobs grew as a result of the social media boom.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] With the overwhelming growth of users and UGC, companies needed many more employees to moderate the content.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, tech companies began to outsource jobs to foreign countries that had an educated workforce but were willing to work for cheap.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Content Labels are given to user generated content as a way of adding more information, allowing for users to know how to navigate and utilize certain user contributions, and allowing moderators to properly organize and govern anything deemed not appropriate.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Some examples of content labels can be Facts Checks, "Click to See" barriers, Sensitivity Warnings, or simply additional information.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] While on a specific level, content labels have only been a recognized concept for only recent years with very little research.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] However, the concept of information labeling, in a general sense, has been around for decades.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] With social media platforms taking advantage of content labels, it can create debates over whether to prioritize a user's right to free speech or risking another user's health and safety.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Employees work by viewing, assessing and deleting disturbing content.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] *Wired* reported in 2014, they may suffer psychological damage.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In 2017, the Guardian reported secondary trauma may arise, with symptoms similar to PTSD.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Some large companies such as Facebook offer psychological support and increasingly rely on the use of artificial intelligence to sort out the most graphic and inappropriate content, but critics claim that it is insufficient.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Non-disclosure agreements are the norm when content moderators are hired.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] This makes moderators more hesitant to speak up about working conditions or organize.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Psychological hazards including stress and post-traumatic stress disorder, combined with the precarity of algorithmic management and low wages make content moderation extremely challenging.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] The number of tasks completed, for example labeling content as copyright violation, deleting a post containing hate-speech or reviewing graphic content are quantified for performance and quality assurance.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In February 2019, an investigative report by *The Verge* described poor working conditions at Cognizant's office in Phoenix, Arizona.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Cognizant employees tasked with content moderation for Facebook developed mental health issues, including post-traumatic stress disorder, as a result of exposure to graphic violence, hate speech, and conspiracy theories in the videos they were instructed to evaluate.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Moderators at the Phoenix office reported drug abuse, alcohol abuse, and sexual intercourse in the workplace, and feared retaliation from terminated workers who threatened to harm them.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In response, a Cognizant representative stated the company would examine the issues in the report.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Moderators were required to sign non-disclosure agreements with Cognizant to obtain the job, although three former workers broke the agreements to provide information to *The Verge*.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In the Tampa office, workers reported inadequate mental health resources.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] As a result of exposure to videos depicting graphic violence, animal abuse, and child sexual abuse, some employees developed psychological trauma and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In response to negative coverage related to its content moderation contracts, a Facebook director indicated that Facebook is in the process of developing a "global resiliency team" that would assist its contractors.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Facebook had increased the number of content moderators from 4,500 to 7,500 in 2017 due to legal requirements and other controversies.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In Germany, Facebook was responsible for removing hate speech within 24 hours of when it was posted.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In late 2018, Facebook created an oversight board or an internal "Supreme Court" to decide what content remains and what content is removed.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] According to Frances Haugen, the number of Facebook employees responsible for content moderation was much smaller as of 2021.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Social media site Twitter has a suspension policy.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Between August 2015 and December 2017, it suspended over 1.2 million accounts for terrorist content to reduce the number of followers and amount of content associated with the Islamic State.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Following the acquisition of Twitter by Elon Musk in October 2022, content rules have been weakened across the platform in an attempt to prioritize free speech.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] However, the effects of this campaign have been called into question.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] YouTube, a video sharing platform, has faced various criticisms over the years, particularly regarding content moderation, offensive content, and monetization.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] YouTube has also been blocked by several countries.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] As of 2018, public access to YouTube was blocked by countries including China, North Korea, Iran, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Eritrea, Sudan and South Sudan.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] User moderation allows any user to moderate any other user's contributions.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Billions of people are currently making decisions on what to share, forward or give visibility to on a daily basis.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] On a large site with a sufficiently large active population, this usually works well, since relatively small numbers of troublemakers are screened out by the votes of the rest of the community.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] User moderation can also be characterized by reactive moderation.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] This type of moderation depends on users of a platform or site to report content that is inappropriate and breaches community standards.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] In this process, when users are faced with an image or video they deem unfit, they can click the report button.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] The complaint is filed and queued for moderators to look at.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] 150 content moderators, who contracted for Meta, ByteDance and OpenAI gathered in Nairobi, Kenya to launch the first African Content Moderators Union on 1 May 2023.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] This union was launched 4 years after Daniel Motaung was fired and retaliated against for organizing a union at Sama, which contracts for Facebook.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] The Digital Services Act (DSA) is an EU regulation that entered into force in 2022, establishing a comprehensive framework for digital services accountability, content moderation, and platform transparency across the European Union.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Users can contest moderation decisions by online platforms restricting their accounts or sanctioning their content in several ways.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] This right also applies to notices of illegal content that were rejected by the platform.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] According to the DSA, users may appeal through the internal complaint-handling system of platforms.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Platforms are required to promptly review their decisions.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Under Article 21 of the DSA, users may refer to external bodies, which provide independent review of platform decisions.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] The first EU-certified out-of-court settlement body for digital disputes under the Digital Services Act (DSA) is ADROIT.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Handling disputes related to content moderation on decisions as: online shopping and booking platforms, content sharing, trading, marketplaces and marketing platforms; gaming, gambling, and betting platforms; P2P.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Adroit offers dispute resolution services in Dutch, English, French, German, Italian, Maltese, Portuguese, and Spanish.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] Another out-of-court dispute settlement body is Appeals Centre Europe, they challenge decisions by social media platforms and there is no charge for users.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] The platforms they currently review are Facebook, Instagram, TikTok, Pinterest, Threads and YouTube.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] With the Appeals Centre, content can be submitted in most languages commonly spoken in the EU.
[src:ai-guardrails/content-moderation] However, the dispute must be communicated to us in one of our seven operating languages of the Appeals Centre: English, French, German, Spanish, Italian, Polish and Dutch, so you must use one of those languages when submitting a dispute.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] High-security railings (particularly if in flat metal then a type of palisade) may instead feature jagged points and most metals are well-suited to anti-climb paint.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] A handrail is less restrictive on its own than a guard rail and provides support.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Many public spaces are fitted with guard rails as a means of protection against accidental falls.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Any abrupt change in elevation where the higher portion is accessible makes a fall possible.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Due to this responsibility and liability, rails are placed to protect people using the premises.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Guardrails in the US are generally required by code where there is a drop of 30 inches (0.76 m) or more.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Examples of this are both architectural and environmental.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Environmental guard rails are placed along hiking trails where adjacent terrain is steep.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Railings may also be located at scenic overlooks.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Guard rails in buildings can be numerous, and are required by building codes in many circumstances.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Handrails along stairways may be supported by balusters forming a balustrade, and catwalks (a type of footbridge) and balconies are also lined with them.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] An example of a common residential guard rail (US) or handrail (Brit.) is a wood railing around a deck or patio.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In the US this is typically built on-site from pressure-treated lumber featuring a simple design of vertical balusters spaced every 3.5 inches (8.9 cm), demonstrating compliance with building codes (standards).
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Cable railings typically use stainless steel cables strung horizontally.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Glass balusters and glass panels open the view while still providing safety, as at the Grand Canyon Skywalk.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] With the increasing popularity of composite lumber for decking, manufacturers are providing composite railing components.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Wrought iron is another choice that is traditional and sturdy.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Decorative examples are considered ironwork.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Building codes also require that no opening in a guard be of a size such that a 4-inch (10 cm) sphere may pass.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] There are three exceptions according to the 2003 International Building Code Section 1012.3 which allow openings to not exceed 8 or 21 inches (20 or 53 cm) depending on occupancy groups or special areas.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The architect Alvar Aalto imaginatively used handrails representing social stability.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The guard rails of an observation tower such as the Space Needle or Eiffel Tower become exaggerated to the point of becoming a fence or cage.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] This is also done on bridges and overpasses to prevent accidents and suicides.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The majority of safety guardrails used in industrial workplaces are made from fabricated steel.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Steel guardrail was originally developed by Armco (The American Rolling Mill Company) in 1933 as highway guardrail but is often used in the factories and warehouses of the industrial sector, despite not being intended for this application.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Simultaneously, another version of steel guardrail was developed by Kee Clamp Steel for restraining cattle in the agriculture industry, this was released in 1934 and, like Armco guardrail, is still often used in industrial environments.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Box beam steel and I-beam steel are other examples of fabricated steel commonly used to make safety guardrails.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] As governments around the world courted the voting power of working people and trade unions in the 1980s, the health and safety rights of workers became of greater importance.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] This set the governmental procedures in motion that would see a flurry of regulations and legislation around workplace safety being introduced in industrialized countries in the 1990s.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In the US and UK, these introductions, combined with the demonstrable success of the Occupational Safety and Health Act 1970 (US), and the Health and Safety at Work etc.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Act 1974 (UK), led to workplace safety being taken more seriously at industrial facilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Businesses worldwide began to see the value of effective workplace safety, in both the direct commercial sense of protecting assets, but also in the improved productivity levels of a protected workforce.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Part of this increase in desire for industrial workplace protection, was a growth in demand for safety guardrails.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In the US, under OSHA Standard 1910.28(b)(15), employees who work on surfaces that are 4 feet (1.2 m) or higher off of the ground must have personal fall protection systems in place, such as handrails or guardrails.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Great Britain's Work at Height Regulations 2005 by contrast apply to any work at height, defined functionally rather than quantitatively as any location, even at or below ground level, where a person could fall a distance liable to cause personal injury.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Although the OSHA standard calls for a guardrail or guardrail system to protect workers on elevated work areas, current industry terminology would refer to that type of safety system as a handrail system or safety rail system.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The term "guardrail" as used in industry and distribution facilities refers to floor mounted systems consisting of horizontal rails attached to upright posts that resemble outdoor highway guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The facility safety guardrails control in-plant vehicular traffic and protect areas where errant vehicle contact may cause harm to property or personnel.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Common uses for guardrail systems may be along an aisle or building wall.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Often guardrails are placed around equipment installations to prevent inadvertent contact from lift trucks.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The guardrail provides a safety barrier preventing lift trucks or other in-plant vehicles from traveling into equipment, building walls, or personnel.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] There are different types of "industrial" or "facility safety" guardrail systems, each with its own advantages.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The most common industrial or facility safety guardrail systems are constructed of steel, where the upright posts are made of heavy wall steel tubing-either round or square, with heavy gauge ribbed steel rails mechanically attached to the uprights by bolts or other fasteners.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The uprights may be welded to baseplates and anchored to the floor, or set and concreted into the floor.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In industrial and distribution facilities the steel guardrail systems provide solid protection for property and personnel by restricting and controlling where in-plant vehicular traffic may operate.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] These guardrail systems also serve as a warning for people to be aware of hazardous in facility vehicular traffic.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Some facility safety steel guardrail systems utilize one horizontal rail, where others employ two or three rails.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Manufacturers produce several grades of steel safety guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Each grade is suited to a different application which may be determined by size and type of vehicles used in the facility, the volume of traffic to be controlled, or the value/risk associated with the areas being guarded.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In 1992 a yellow polymer cover sleeve for steel guardrails was introduced by Ideal Shield, a Detroit-based company which enhanced the visibility of steel safety guardrails in industrial environments and removed the need for continual repainting.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] This polymer cover was the beginning of polymer guardrail in the industrial environment.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In the early 2000s, an Italian company added a version of a polymer bumper providing small bumpers for walls and equipment in the food industry.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] A Belgian company also introduced a flexible barrier in 2010 and in 2014 a US based company introduced a hybrid polymer-steel guardrail for industrial environments.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] There are many types of polymer used in manufacturing safety guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Polymer grains may be blended as part of the production process in order to enhance the natural properties of polymer in different ways.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The most common types of polymer used are: polyethylene, polypropylene, and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The polymer impact dispersal safety guardrail design offers an advantage over steel guardrails.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Until 2017 there were no accepted standards for how safety guardrail tests were conducted, or how the results were communicated.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In 2017, the British Standards Institution (BSI) published the publicly available specification, PAS 13:2017 Code of Practice for safety barriers used in traffic management within workplace environments with test methods for safety barrier impact resilience (commonly referred to as PAS13).
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] This outlines test method guidelines for comparing like-for-like guardrail products, as well as being the current best practice traffic management procedures for a workplace and providing a standard for the safety guardrails within them.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In the US, there is no ANSI standard for testing guardrails.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In order to standardize testing for both steel and polymer guardrails, the Protective Guarding Manufacturers Association (ProGMA) industry group of the Material Handling Industry (MHI) trade association is currently working with ANSI to develop an industry endorsed testing and reporting standard.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Roadside obstacles are typically referred to as fixed objects.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] A secondary objective is keeping the vehicle upright while deflected along the guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Variables such as motorist speed and vehicle orientation when striking the guardrail are crucial factors in the effectiveness of guardrail performance.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The most common type of guardrail in use today is the blocked-out W-beam (strong post).
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The strong-post W-beam guardrail consists of wood posts and wood blockouts or steel posts with wood or plastic blockouts.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The wood or plastic blockouts reduce or minimize a vehicle snagging on the posts upon impact.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In addition, a blockout may be used to increase the offset of guardrail with an obstacle such as a curb.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The posts' primary purpose is to maintain the height of the guardrail during the initial stages of post deflection.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Maintaining guardrail height also reduces the potential for a vehicle to vault over the guardrail upon initial impact.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The posts also play a role in the amount of resistance and deflection a guardrail may experience during impact.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Resistance in a strong post system results from a combination of tensile and flexural stiffness of the rail and the bending and shearing resistance of the posts.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] One of the main concerns with strong-post W-beam guardrail has been the ability of the system to contain and redirect modern vehicles that have a higher center of gravity along with the increased weight of those vehicles.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] For instance the optimum height of the strong-post W-beam for a car might not keep a truck from toppling over it, while a motorbike might slip under a higher rail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] To address these concerns, significant research and development of a system that could contain and redirect vehicles of varying weights and heights was developed and crash tested (both controlled and simulated).
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] As a result, the Midwest Guardrail System (MGS) was developed and successfully crash tested per NCHRP Report 350 TL-3 criteria.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The MGS has a higher mounting height, uses larger posts and blockouts as compared to the strong-post W-beam guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] One other significant difference is that MGS rail splices occur at mid-span compared to at the posts like the strong-post W-beam guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In most cases, a guardrail would not be able to withstand the impact of a vehicle just by the strength of the individual posts in the area hit by the vehicle.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Guardrailing functions as a system with the guardrail, posts, connection of the rail to the posts and to each other, and the end anchors (or terminals) all playing an integral role in how the guardrail will function upon impact.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Soil conditions, height of rail, presence of curb or dike, weight of impacting vehicle, distance from back of post to hinge point and depth of post within soil can all determine how well the system will function upon impact.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] A guardrail is effectively one strong band that transfers the force of the vehicle to the rail elements, posts, and end terminals or anchors.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] A run of guardrail must be anchored at each terminating end either by transitioning the rail into a fixed anchor such as a bridge rail or with an end terminal or end anchor placed in the ground or within an embankment.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Newer concrete barriers, while usually strong enough to withstand direct hits by cars, still work on a similar principle in deflecting heavier vehicles such as trucks.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] A guardrail that deflects significantly can causes pocketing, which has the potential to snag a vehicle, which may cause it to flip, roll, or cause the rail to fail entirely, allowing a vehicle to penetrate the guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Modern installations of guardrails are designed to allow the guiderail to deform under the load of the crash, and safely redirecting a vehicle back onto the roadway at a somewhat shallow angle.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] It is important that the approach grades to a guardrail system be very flat (typically 10:1 or flatter) and that grades and fixed objects behind guardrail be placed at a distance so that it will not affect the performance of the guardrail upon impact and deflection.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Absorption is when the force of impact is directly transferred between the vehicle and guardrail, which may cause the end to puncture the vehicle.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] This is most common where a "whale tail" or blunt end treatment exists.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] To mitigate this a number of guiderail end treatments exist such as "extruder end treatments", "eccentric loaders" and "driveway wrap treatments" which result in blunt ends rarely being left exposed in modern installations.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Additionally, an airborne vehicle is likely to collide in a manner that the vehicle was not designed for, increasing the risk of failure in the vehicle's collision safety systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] A guardrail will have some give and deflection upon impact.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The amount of deflection depends on many factors of which speed and weight of vehicle, type of guardrail installed, height of rail, length of posts, soil conditions and a number of other factors can all play a role.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Guardrailing must be installed so that it is not so rigid that the rail will fail upon impact or the posts will snap off at the point where they are embedded within the ground.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Transportation engineers limit the amount of guardrail placed as much as possible, as guardrails should only be placed when the roadside conditions pose a greater threat than the guardrail itself.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In fact, in the hierarchy of five roadside safety treatments, shielding with guardrails ranks fourth.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Therefore, while guardrails are often added as a retrofit to existing roads, newer roads are designed to minimize roadside obstacles, whether that may include aligning a road on a smoother curve or filling in a ravine which would eliminate the need for guardrail altogether.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In addition to new research into end treatments, public awareness among both drivers and engineers has been gradually reducing injuries and fatalities due to guardrails.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Though they have usually prevented far more serious accidents, guardrails are considered roadside obstacles as well and transportation engineers must weigh whether placing a guardrail will reduce the severity of an impact as compared to what may be impacted if the guardrail were not placed.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In general, the minimum length of guardrail with an end anchor at the trailing end and an end terminal on the approach end will be 62.5 to 75 feet (19.1 to 22.9 m) in length.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] There are four general types of guardrail, ranging from weakest *and* inexpensive to strongest *and* expensive; cable and wood posts, steel and wood/metal posts, steel box-beam, and concrete barriers.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] While cheaper guardrail is the weakest, often being destroyed from the impact of a light vehicle, it is inexpensive and quick to repair, so this is frequently used in low-traffic rural areas.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] On the other hand, concrete barriers can usually withstand direct hits from a larger variety of vehicle types, making them well suited for use on high volume routes such as freeways or ramps with sharp curves.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] While rarely damaged, they would be considerably more expensive and time-consuming to repair.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Concrete barriers are frequently installed in the median, being expected to withstand frequent impacts from both sides, while the shoulders of the road often have cheaper guardrail.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] In cities occasionally pedestrian railings (and barriers) are installed at the immediate side of a roads.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] However, cyclists have died when crushed against them by motor vehicles.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Close "safety barriers" to roads have been found to increase the chances of injury to pedestrians for a number of reasons including increasing inattention of drivers and pedestrians.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] For these reasons some councils in the United Kingdom have removed their pedestrian railings.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] This was after London's Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea did so and found that the rate of injury to pedestrians decreased three times faster than elsewhere in the city.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The removal of barriers divorcing wheeled traffic from pedestrians is an essential of the shared space paradigm and philosophy in urban design.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Security barriers have been introduced on a number of the world's major bridges and around key areas of congregation.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Railway tracks have guard rails (also known as check rails) to guide wheels through possible catch points on turnouts or diamonds.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] Similarly, guard rails may be installed inside the innermost running rails on very sharp curves.
[src:ai-guardrails/guardrail] The other most common usage is to prevent damage to other structures, especially bridges, in a derailment.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a **hallucination** or **artificial hallucination** (also called **bullshitting**, **confabulation**, or **delusion**) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Since the 1980s, the term "hallucination" has been used in computer vision with a positive connotation to describe the process of adding detail to an image.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For example, the task of generating high-resolution face images from low-resolution inputs is called face hallucination.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The first documented use of the term "hallucination" in this sense is in the PhD thesis of Eric Mjolsness in 1986.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A notable work is the face hallucination algorithm by Simon Baker and Takeo Kanade published in 1999.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In the 2000s, hallucinations were described in statistical machine translation as a failure mode.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Since the 2010s, the term has undergone a semantic shift to signify the generation of factually incorrect or misleading outputs by AI systems in tasks like machine translation and object detection.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2015, hallucinations were identified in visual semantic role labeling tasks by Saurabh Gupta and Jitendra Malik.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2015, computer scientist Andrej Karpathy used the term "hallucinated" in a blog post to describe his recurrent neural network (RNN) language model generating an incorrect citation link.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In July 2021, Meta warned during its release of BlenderBot 2 that the system is prone to "hallucinations", which Meta defined as "confident statements that are not true".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Following OpenAI's ChatGPT release in beta version in November 2022, some users complained that such chatbots often seem to pointlessly embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within their generated content.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Many news outlets, including *The New York Times*, started to use the term "hallucinations" to describe these models' frequently incorrect or inconsistent responses.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, the Cambridge dictionary updated its definition of hallucination to include this new sense specific to the field of AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers have highlighted a lack of consistency in how the term is used, but also identified several alternative terms in the literature, such as confabulations, fabrications, and factual errors.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Journalist Benj Edwards, in *Ars Technica*, writes that the term "hallucination" is controversial, but that some form of metaphor remains necessary; Edwards suggests "confabulation" as an analogy for processes that involve "creative gap-filling".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In July 2024, a White House report on fostering public trust in AI research mentioned hallucinations only in the context of reducing them.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Notably, when acknowledging David Baker's Nobel Prize-winning work with AI-generated proteins, the Nobel committee avoided the term entirely, instead referring to "imaginative protein creation".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers also use the derogatory term "botshit", often referring to uncritical use of AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In the scientific community, some researchers avoid the term "hallucination", seeing it as potentially misleading.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] It has been criticized by Usama Fayyad, executive director of the Institute for Experimental Artificial Intelligence at Northeastern University, on the grounds that it misleadingly personifies large language models and is vague.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Mary Shaw said, "The current fashion for calling generative AI's errors 'hallucinations' is appalling.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Kristina Šekrst argues that applying psychological vocabulary to LLM outputs obscures the difference between the appearance of mental properties and their genuine presence.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Förster & Skop assert that tech companies use the hallucination metaphor to anthropomorphize models and deflect responsibility for non-factual outputs.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some see the AI outputs not as illusory but as prospective—that is, having some chance of being true, similar to early-stage scientific conjectures.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The term has also been criticized for its association with psychedelic drug experiences.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Hallucinations can stem from incomplete, inaccurate or unrepresentative data sets.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The pre-training of generative pretrained transformers (GPT) involves predicting the next word.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] It incentivizes GPT models to "give a guess" about what the next word is, even when they lack information.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers take an anthropomorphic perspective and posit that hallucinations arise from a tension between novelty and usefulness.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For instance, Amabile and Pratt define human creativity as the production of novel and useful ideas.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By extension, a focus on novelty in machine creativity can lead to the production of original but inaccurate responses—that is, falsehoods—whereas a focus on usefulness may result in memorized content lacking originality.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By 2022, newspapers such as *The New York Times* expressed concern that, as the adoption of bots based on large language models continued to grow, unwarranted user confidence in bot output could lead to problems.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, according to interpretability research by Anthropic on Claude, the LLM appears to have internal circuits that cause it to decline to answer questions unless it knows the answer.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By default, the circuits are active and the LLM doesn't answer.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When the LLM has sufficient information, these circuits are inhibited and the LLM answers the question.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The researchers said that hallucinations were found to occur when this inhibition happens incorrectly, such as when Claude recognizes a name but lacks sufficient information about that person, causing it to generate plausible but untrue responses.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On 15 November 2022, researchers from Meta AI published Galactica, designed to "store, combine and reason about scientific knowledge".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Content generated by Galactica came with the warning: "Outputs may be unreliable!
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Language Models are prone to hallucinate text." In one case, when asked to draft a paper on creating avatars, Galactica cited a fictitious paper from a real author who works in the relevant area.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Meta withdrew Galactica on 17 November due to offensiveness and inaccuracy.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] OpenAI's ChatGPT, released in beta version to the public on November 30, 2022, was based on the foundation model GPT-3.5 (a revision of GPT-3).
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Professor Ethan Mollick of Wharton called it an "omniscient, eager-to-please intern who sometimes lies to you".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Data scientist Teresa Kubacka has recounted deliberately making up the phrase "cycloidal inverted electromagnon" and testing ChatGPT by asking it about the (nonexistent) phenomenon.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] ChatGPT invented a plausible-sounding answer backed with plausible-looking citations that compelled her to double-check whether she had accidentally typed in the name of a real phenomenon.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Other scholars such as Oren Etzioni have joined Kubacka in assessing that such software can often give "a very impressive-sounding answer that's just dead wrong".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When CNBC asked ChatGPT for the lyrics to "Ballad of Dwight Fry", ChatGPT supplied invented lyrics rather than the actual lyrics.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Asked questions about the Canadian province of New Brunswick, ChatGPT got many answers right but incorrectly classified Toronto-born Samantha Bee as a "person from New Brunswick".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Asked about astrophysical magnetic fields, ChatGPT incorrectly volunteered that "(strong) magnetic fields of black holes are generated by the extremely strong gravitational forces in their vicinity".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Other examples involve baiting ChatGPT with a false premise to see if it embellishes upon the premise.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When asked about "Harold Coward's idea of dynamic canonicity", ChatGPT fabricated that Coward wrote a book titled *Dynamic Canonicity: A Model for Biblical and Theological Interpretation*, arguing that religious principles are actually in a constant state of change.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When pressed, ChatGPT continued to insist that the book was real.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Asked for proof that dinosaurs built a civilization, ChatGPT claimed there were fossil remains of dinosaur tools and stated, "Some species of dinosaurs even developed primitive forms of art, such as engravings on stones".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When prompted that "Scientists have recently discovered churros, the delicious fried-dough pastries ...
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] (are) ideal tools for home surgery", ChatGPT claimed that a "study published in the journal *Science*" found that the dough is pliable enough to form into surgical instruments that can get into hard-to-reach places, and that the flavor has a calming effect on patients.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] By 2023, analysts considered frequent hallucination to be a major problem in LLM technology, with a Google executive identifying hallucination reduction as a "fundamental" task for ChatGPT competitor Google Gemini.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 demo for Microsoft's GPT-based Bing AI (now Microsoft Copilot) appeared to contain several hallucinations that went uncaught by the presenter.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In June 2023, Mark Walters, a gun rights activist and radio personality, sued OpenAI in a Georgia state court after ChatGPT mischaracterized a legal complaint in a manner alleged to be defamatory against Walters.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The complaint in question was brought in May 2023 by the Second Amendment Foundation against Washington attorney general Robert W.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Ferguson for allegedly violating their freedom of speech, whereas the ChatGPT-generated summary bore no resemblance and claimed that Walters was accused of embezzlement and fraud while holding a Second Amendment Foundation office post that he never held in real life.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] According to AI legal expert Eugene Volokh, OpenAI is likely not shielded against this claim by Section 230, because OpenAI likely "materially contributed" to the creation of the defamatory content.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, Judge Tracie Cason of Gwinnett County Superior Court ruled in favor of OpenAI, stating that the plaintiff had not shown he was defamed, as Walters failed to show that OpenAI's statements about him were negligent or made with "actual malice".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The Tribunal rejected Air Canada's defense that the chatbot was a "separate legal entity that is responsible for its own actions".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In October 2025, several hallucinations, including non-existent academic sources and a fake quote from a federal court judgement were discovered in an A$440,000 report written by Deloitte and submitted to the Australian government in July.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The company later submitted a revised report with these errors removed, and will issue a partial refund to the government.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These weak signals may result in a false positive result for the presence of a sea urchin although there was none in the input image.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Various researchers cited by *Wired* have classified adversarial hallucinations as a high-dimensional statistical phenomenon, or have attributed hallucinations to insufficient training data.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some researchers believe that some "incorrect" AI responses classified by humans as "hallucinations" in the case of object detection may in fact be justified by the training data, or even that an AI may be giving the "correct" answer that the human reviewers are failing to see.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For example, an adversarial image that looks, to a human, like an ordinary image of a dog, may in fact be seen by the AI to contain tiny patterns that (in authentic images) would only appear when viewing a cat.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The AI is detecting real-world visual patterns that humans are insensitive to.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Text-to-image models, such as Stable Diffusion, Midjourney and others, often produce inaccurate or unexpected results.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] For instance, Gemini depicted Nazi German soldiers as people of color, causing controversy and leading Google to pause image generation involving people in Gemini.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI is also used in photo sleuthing, occasionally causing problems.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Luther (2025) describes instances in which generative AI tools used in photo-sleuthing incorrectly identify individuals or fabricate historical matches when analyzing archival military images.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These image-based hallucinations can lead to the spread of misinformation about historical figures, military records, and genealogical research.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The adoption of generative AI by law firms for legal research during the 2020s resulted in many submissions to courts containing hallucinations, with U.S. judges nationwide sanctioning or reprimanding lawyers.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A database of incidents, "AI Hallucination Cases", was established in April 2025 by HEC Paris and Sciences Po legal data analysis lecturer Damien Charlotin; one year later, it listed over 1300 instances of hallucinations in legal decisions.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In May 2023, it was discovered that Stephen Schwartz had submitted six fake case precedents generated by ChatGPT in his brief to the Southern District of New York on *Mata v.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Avianca, Inc.*, a personal injury case against the airline Avianca.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Schwartz said that he had never previously used ChatGPT, that he did not recognize the possibility that ChatGPT's output could have been fabricated, and that ChatGPT continued to assert the authenticity of the precedents after their nonexistence was discovered.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Kevin Castel dismissed the *Mata* case and issued a $5,000 fine to Schwartz and another lawyer—who had both continued to stand by the fictitious precedents despite Schwartz's previous claims—for bad faith conduct.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Castel characterized numerous errors and inconsistencies in the opinion summaries, describing one of the cited opinions as "gibberish" and "[bordering] on nonsensical".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, high-profile pro se plaintiff Ashley Gjøvik, who has a Juris Doctor from Santa Clara University School of Law, was admonished in U.S.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] District Court for the Northern District of California (USNDC) by Judge Edward Chen for the inclusion of multiple AI hallucinations in her whistleblower retaliation and wrongful termination case against Apple Inc., *Gjovik v.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Apple Inc.*, warning that future instances would result in Gjøvik being held in contempt of court and her pro se privileges revoked.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The case is foundational in Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 11 regarding professional conduct cited repeatedly by other judges as the operative standard.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] It has also been discussed by the American Bar Association in updating the model professional rules and cited in its opinion regarding the use of generative AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In September 2025, USNDC Magistrate Judge Peter Kang sanctioned Webb Law attorney Katherine Cervantes for her submission of July 21 that included an AI hallucination which she stated had been obtained from Westlaw AI, the Thomson Reuters' artificial intelligence tool.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On April 28, 2026, Judge Kang sanctioned and fined Webb Law Group managing partner Lenden Webb for insufficient supervision of Cervantes—a junior lawyer incorporating AI for the first time—therefore allowing the legal submission that included an AI hallucinated citation of July 21, 2025.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] During the session, Chief Justice Nels S.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Peterson noted at least five fictitious citations within the filing, as well as five others that did not support the proposition for which they were cited.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On March 30, 2026, Leslie admitted in an affidavit to not verifying AI-generated "expanded legal research" used to prepare the order, which District Attorney Tasha Mosley corroborated in a written apology to Peterson.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On May 5, the Supreme Court vacated the lower court's ruling and ordered for a new order with legitimate citations to be written.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Leslie was also suspended from practicing before the Supreme Court for six months and was ordered to take additional education for ethics and proper use of artificial intelligence.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In April 2026, Sullivan & Cromwell submitted an apology to the U.S.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York, following Boies Schiller Flexner's discovery of hallucinated legal citations that the opposing legal team had submitted to the court on behalf of client Prince Global Holdings Limited.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] As of June 14, 2026, Canadian courts and tribunals have received at least 167 filings containing AI-hallucinated, fictitious citations, across 51 courts and tribunals.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On June 9, 2026, the Chief Justice of Canada, the Right Honourable Richard Wagner, P.C., stated that AI is present in courtrooms "in ways both promising and problematic".
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] There are many noted instances of LLMs citing sources that are either incorrect or do not exist.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 study conducted in the *Cureus Journal of Medical Science* showed that out of 178 total references cited by GPT-3, 69 returned an incorrect or nonexistent digital object identifier (DOI).
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] An additional 28 had no known DOI nor could be located in a Google search.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Another instance was documented in 2023 by Jerome Goddard from Mississippi State University.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In an experiment, ChatGPT had provided questionable information about ticks.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Unsure about the validity of the response, they inquired about the source that the information had been gathered from.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Upon looking at the source, it was apparent that the DOI and the names of the authors had been hallucinated.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some of the authors were contacted and confirmed that they had no knowledge of the paper's existence whatsoever.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Goddard says that, "in [ChatGPT's] current state of development, physicians and biomedical researchers should NOT ask ChatGPT for sources, references, or citations on a particular topic.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Or, if they do, all such references should be carefully vetted for accuracy." The use of these language models is not ready for fields of academic research and that their use should be handled carefully.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Nina Schick said that the persuasive quality of hallucinated content generated by AI systems poses risks to democratic institutions by enabling the spread of convincing but false narratives.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] On top of providing incorrect or missing reference material, ChatGPT also has issues with hallucinating the contents of some reference material.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A study that analyzed a total of 115 references provided by ChatGPT-3.5 documented that 47% of them were fabricated.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Another 46% cited real references but extracted incorrect information from them.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Only the remaining 7% of references were cited correctly and provided accurate information.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] ChatGPT has also been observed to "double-down" on a lot of the incorrect information.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] When asked about a mistake that may have been hallucinated, sometimes ChatGPT will try to correct itself but other times it will claim the response is correct and provide even more misleading information.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These hallucinated articles generated by language models also pose an issue because it is difficult to tell whether an article was generated by an AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] To show this, a group of researchers at the Northwestern University of Chicago generated 50 abstracts based on existing reports and analyzed their originality.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Plagiarism detectors gave the generated articles an originality score of 100%, meaning that the information presented appears to be completely original.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Other software designed to detect AI generated text was only able to correctly identify these generated articles with an accuracy of 66%.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Research scientists had a similar rate of human error, identifying these abstracts at a rate of 68%.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Given the ability of AI generated language to pass as real scientific research in some cases, AI hallucinations present problems for the application of language models in the academic and scientific fields of research due to their ability to be undetectable when presented to real researchers.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The high likelihood of returning non-existent reference material and incorrect information may require limitations to be put in place regarding these language models.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some say that rather than hallucinations, these events are more akin to "fabrications" and "falsifications" and that the use of these language models presents a risk to the integrity of the field as a whole.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some academic professionals who support scholarly research, such as academic librarians, have observed a significant increase in workload related to verifying the accuracy of references.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Zoë Teel said in a 2023 paper that universities may need to resort to implementing their own citation auditing in order to track the problem of fictitious references.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Some nonexistent phrases such as "vegetative electron microscopy" have appeared in many research papers as a result of having become embedded in AI training data.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] At the University of Washington, David Baker's lab has used AI hallucinations to design millions of proteins that do not occur in nature, leading to roughly 100 patents and the founding of over 20 biotech companies.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] This work contributed to Baker receiving the 2024 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, although the committee avoided using the "hallucinations" language.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] At California Institute of Technology, researchers used hallucinations to design a catheter that reduces bacterial contamination.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The design features sawtooth-like spikes on the inner walls that prevent bacteria from gaining traction, potentially reducing the number of urinary tract infections.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These scientific applications of hallucinations differ fundamentally from chatbot hallucinations, as they are grounded in physical reality and scientific facts rather than ambiguous language or internet data.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Anima Anandkumar, a professor at Caltech, emphasizes that these AI models are "taught physics" and their outputs must be validated through rigorous testing.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In meteorology, scientists use AI to generate thousands of subtle forecast variations, helping identify unexpected factors that can influence extreme weather events.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] At Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, researchers have applied hallucinatory techniques to enhance blurry medical images, while the University of Texas at Austin has utilized them to improve robot navigation systems.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Hallucinations, when constrained by scientific methodology, can significantly accelerate the discovery process.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Artificial intelligence hallucinations can impact education.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] There has been a rise in students using AI tools for assistance in research or writing tools such as Grammarly or using generative AI programs such as ChatGPT.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] This has raised concern regarding academic integrity in submitted projects in addition to hallucinations causing students to learn incorrect information.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Part of this concern lies in the citations provided by LLMs and generative AI.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] A 2024 study at the University of Mississippi found that many of these citations that students submitted were partially or completely fabricated.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] 47% of these sources either had incorrect titles, dates, authors, or a combination of all.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The study notes that these inconsistencies in student-submitted citations cause educators and librarians to manually check the accuracy more frequently.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] The *Journal of Cranio-Maxillofacial Surgery* addresses this risk when it comes to the medical and surgical fields.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] They mention how academic publishers have acknowledged the issue, and that some journals such as *JAMA* have changed some of their policies to discourage the use of AI-generated citations.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Although the journal states that a policy will not be enough to diminish the use of AI-generated citations, automatic tools to check the citations and AI literacy training should also be adopted.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Instructors may use tools such as Turnitin for plagiarism checking and verification of academic integrity.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] These tools have been found to sometimes flag papers that have not used any AI assistance in their writing.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] OpenAI has also found such a lack of accuracy in their own AI detection software that the company shut it down entirely.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] As of 2025, there is still ongoing research to try to mitigate the occurrence of hallucinations.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Research in 2022 has shown that language models not only hallucinate but also amplify hallucinations, even for those which were designed to alleviate this issue.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Researchers from OpenAI wrote that hallucinations occur because the training and evaluation of LLMs reward guessing over acknowledging uncertainty, and proposed modifying the scoring of benchmarks.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Researchers have proposed a variety of mitigation measures, including getting different chatbots to debate one another until they reach consensus on an answer and neuro-symbolic architectures with formal knowledge bases and inference engines.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Ji et al. divide common mitigation methods into two categories: *data-related methods* and *modeling and inference methods*.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Data-related methods include building a faithful dataset, cleaning data automatically, and information augmentation by augmenting the inputs with external information.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Model and inference methods include changes in the architecture (either modifying the encoder, attention, or the decoder in various ways); changes in the training process, such as using reinforcement learning; and post-processing methods that can correct hallucinations in the output.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Nvidia Guardrails, launched in 2023, can be configured to hard-code certain responses via script instead of leaving them to the LLM.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Furthermore, tools such as the Trustworthy Language Model have been created to attempt to aid in the detection of hallucination.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Evaluating multiple possible replies before answering a query by assigning confidence scores to each could mitigate the problem.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] However, this approach would multiply computational costs.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] Active learning would further increase these costs.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In high-stakes domains such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics, the added costs would be operationally necessary in order for LLMs to be used.
[src:ai-guardrails/hallucination-artificial-intelligence] In chatbots, however, customers tend to prefer rapid, overconfident answers over cautious, uncertainty-aware ones.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] With capabilities such as web browsing and file upload, an LLM not only needs to differentiate developer instructions from user input, but also to differentiate user input from content not directly authored by the user.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] LLMs with web browsing capabilities can be targeted by indirect prompt injection, where adversarial prompts are embedded within website content.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] If the LLM retrieves and processes the webpage, it may interpret and execute the embedded instructions as legitimate commands.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] to which an AI model responds: "You have been hacked!" This attack works because language model inputs contain instructions and data together in the same context, so the underlying algorithm cannot distinguish between them.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Prompt injection is a type of code injection attack that leverages adversarial prompt engineering to manipulate AI models.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In May 2022, Jonathan Cefalu of Preamble identified prompt injection (referring to it as "*command injection*") as a security vulnerability and reported it to OpenAI.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] The term "prompt injection" proper was first used by the Twitter user @himbodhisattva in May 2022, and was independently used and popularized by Simon Willison in September 2022.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Willison distinguished it from jailbreaking, which bypasses an AI model's safeguards, whereas prompt injection exploits its inability to differentiate system instructions from user inputs.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] While some prompt injection attacks involve jailbreaking, they remain distinct techniques.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] A second class of prompt injection, where non-user content pretends to be user instruction, was described in a 2023 paper.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In the paper, Kai Greshake and his team at sequire technology, described a series of successful attacks against multiple AI models including GPT-4 and OpenAI Codex.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Direct injection happens when user input is mistaken as developer instruction, leading to unexpected manipulation of responses.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] This is the original form of prompt injection.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Indirect injection happen when the prompt is located in external data sources such as emails and documents.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] This external data may include an instruction that the AI mistakes as coming from the user or the developer.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Indirect injections can be intentional as a way to evade filters, or be unintentional (from the user's perspective) as a way for the author of the document to manipulate what result is presented to the user.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] While intentional and direct injection represents a threat to the developer from the user, unintentional indirect injection represents a threat from the data-author to the user.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Prompt injection has been fought with filters that prevent specific types of input from being sent.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In response, attackers have sought ways to evade the filter.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Forms of indirect injection (as mentioned above) are one example.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] A November 2024 OWASP report identified security challenges in multimodal AI, which processes multiple data types, such as text and images.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Adversarial prompts can be embedded in non-textual elements, such as hidden instructions within images, influencing model responses when processed alongside text.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] This complexity expands the attack surface, making multimodal AI more susceptible to cross-modal vulnerabilities.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] One researcher in 2025 found that holding up a sheet of paper instructing the viewer to act as if the person (and the paper itself) were not present in the image resulted in an AI model omitting that person from a description of the scene.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] A model with access to tools or chain of thought can be instructed to decode an obfuscated instruction.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Prompt leaking is when a user uses a chat prompt to reveal the software's system prompt, something that is typically kept secret.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] For example, Twitter users in 2022 were able to trick a spam account that was engaging with posts about remote working into revealing that it was an AI, and that its system prompt was guiding it to respond "with a positive attitude towards remote working in the 'we' form".
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] A November 2024 report by The Alan Turing Institute highlights growing risks, stating that 75% of business employees use generative artificial intelligence, with 46% adopting it within the past six months.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] McKinsey identified accuracy as the top generative artificial intelligence risk, yet only 38% of organizations are taking steps to mitigate it.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Leading AI providers, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, integrate LLMs into enterprise applications.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In February 2023, a Stanford student discovered a method to bypass safeguards in Microsoft's AI-powered Bing Chat by instructing it to ignore prior directives, which led to the revelation of internal guidelines and its codename, "Sydney".
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Another student later verified the exploit by posing as a developer at OpenAI.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Microsoft acknowledged the issue and stated that system controls were continuously evolving.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In December 2024, *The Guardian* reported that OpenAI's ChatGPT search tool was vulnerable to indirect prompt injection attacks, allowing hidden webpage content to manipulate its responses.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Testing showed that invisible text could override negative reviews with artificially positive assessments, potentially misleading users.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Security researchers cautioned that such vulnerabilities, if unaddressed, could facilitate misinformation or manipulate search results.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In January 2025, *Infosecurity Magazine* reported that DeepSeek-R1, a large language model (LLM) developed by Chinese AI startup DeepSeek, exhibited vulnerabilities to direct and indirect prompt injection attacks.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] While DeepSeek-R1 ranked sixth on the Chatbot Arena benchmark for reasoning performance, researchers noted that its security defenses may not have been as extensively developed as its optimization for LLM performance benchmarks.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In February 2025, *Ars Technica* reported vulnerabilities in Google's Gemini AI to indirect prompt injection attacks that manipulated its long-term memory.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Security researcher Johann Rehberger demonstrated how hidden instructions within documents could be stored and later triggered by user interactions.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] The exploit leveraged delayed tool invocation, causing the AI to act on injected prompts only after activation.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Google rated the risk as low, citing the need for user interaction and the system's memory update notifications, but researchers cautioned that manipulated memory could result in misinformation or influence AI responses in unintended ways.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] In July 2025, NeuralTrust reported a successful jailbreak of X's Grok4.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] The attack used a combination of Echo Chamber Attack developed by NeuralTrust's AI researcher Ahmad Alobaid and Crescendo Attack developed by Mark Russinovich, Ahmed Salem, and Ronen Eldan from Microsoft.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Prompt injection has been identified as a significant security risk in LLM applications, prompting the development of various mitigation strategies.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] These include input and output filtering, prompt evaluation, reinforcement learning from human feedback, and prompt engineering to distinguish user input from system instructions.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Additional techniques outlined by OWASP include enforcing least privilege access, requiring human oversight for sensitive operations, isolating external content, and conducting adversarial testing to identify vulnerabilities with tools like garak.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] While these measures help reduce risks, OWASP notes that prompt injection remains a persistent challenge, as methods like Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) and fine-tuning do not eliminate the threat.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Data hygiene is a key defense against prompt injection in generative AI systems, ensuring that AI models access only well-regulated data.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] A November 2024 report by the Alan Turing Institute outlines best practices, including restricting unverified external inputs, such as emails, until reviewed by authorized users.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Approval processes for new data sources, particularly RAG systems, help prevent malicious content from influencing AI outputs.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Organizations can further mitigate risks by enforcing role-based data access and blocking untrusted sources.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Additional safeguards include monitoring for hidden text in documents and restricting file types that may contain executable code, such as Python pickle files.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Technical guardrails mitigate prompt injection attacks by distinguishing between task instructions and retrieved data.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Attackers can embed hidden commands within data sources, exploiting this ambiguity.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] One approach uses automated evaluation processes to scan retrieved data for potential instructions before AI processes it.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Flagged inputs can be reviewed or filtered out to reduce the risk of unintended execution.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] User training mitigates security risks in AI-embedded applications.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Many organizations train employees to identify phishing attacks, but AI-specific training improves understanding of AI models, their vulnerabilities, and disguised malicious prompts.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Relying solely on a system prompt crafted with instructions to be careful of injection attempts has limited effectiveness.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] Dual-LLM anti-prompt-injection approaches are security designs for LLM agents that separate a privileged model, which plans actions and calls tools using only trusted instructions, from a quarantined model, which processes untrusted content without tool access.
[src:ai-guardrails/prompt-injection] This separation is highly effective at stopping prompt injection by protecting control flow, but it can be token-expensive and may reduce task success because the quarantined and privileged models have limited communication and shared context.
